  "text": "# AddressSanitizer Implementation Findings\n\n## LLVM (github.com/sg-evals/llvm-project--a8f3c97d)\n\n### 1. ASan Interceptors: compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_interceptors.cpp\nThis C++ source file implements AddressSanitizer interceptors for standard library functions. It intercepts various libc functions like memcpy, strcpy, malloc, free, and other memory-related functions. The file is marked as \"Part of AddressSanitizer, an address sanity checker\" and uses the INTERCEPTOR macro to hook into libc functions. Key includes: asan_allocator.h, asan_internal.h, asan_mapping.h, asan_poisoning.h, asan_report.h, and other core asan headers.\n\n### 2. ASan Runtime Initialization: compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_rtl.cpp\nThis C++ source file implements the ASan runtime library's main initialization and core functionality. It is the main file of the ASan run-time library containing the initialization logic. The file includes critical components like asan_activation.h, asan_allocator.h, asan_fake_stack.h, asan_interceptors.h, asan_interface_internal.h, and handles shadow memory setup, die callbacks, and runtime initialization.\n\n### 3. LLVM IR Instrumentation Pass: llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp\nThis C++ source file implements the LLVM IR-level instrumentation pass that inserts AddressSanitizer checks at compile time. The primary struct is `AddressSanitizer` (defined at line 775), which instruments code in a module to find memory bugs. It implements the IR transformation pass that adds shadow memory checks before every memory instruction. The pass is part of LLVM's instrumentation transformation pipeline, as shown in the CMakeLists.txt.\n\n## GCC (github.com/sg-evals/gcc--96dfb333)\n\n### 4. ASan Instrumentation Implementation: gcc/asan.cc\nThis C++ source file implements AddressSanitizer instrumentation in GCC. It describes the AddressSanitizer algorithm with both an instrumentation module (this file) and a run-time library. The instrumentation adds run-time checks before every memory instruction using shadow memory offsets. The file includes comprehensive comments explaining the algorithm and includes all necessary GCC backend headers (gimple.h, cfghooks.h, gimplify.h, etc.).\n\n### 5. ASan Header: gcc/asan.h\nThis header file provides the interface for ASan functionality in GCC. It declares external functions for ASan instrumentation and HWASan (Hardware AddressSanitizer) functionality, including asan_function_start(), asan_finish_file(), asan_emit_stack_protection(), asan_expand_check_ifn(), and related hardware-based memory tagging functions. It serves as the main include for ASan-related declarations in the GCC compiler.\n\n## Cross-Compiler Summary\n\nBoth LLVM and GCC implement AddressSanitizer with similar architectural components:\n- **Interceptor/Hook Layer**: LLVM uses asan_interceptors.cpp to intercept libc functions\n- **Runtime Core**: Both implement initialization and core runtime in separate files (asan_rtl.cpp in LLVM)\n- **Compiler Pass**: LLVM's instrumentation pass directly in AddressSanitizer.cpp, while GCC uses the asan.cc module\n- **API Interface**: LLVM uses asan_interface_internal.h while GCC uses asan.h header declarations\n\nBoth use a shadow memory scheme where memory accesses are instrumented at compile time to check shadow memory before allowing access, enabling detection of out-of-bounds and use-after-free errors."
}

